      The deli
   =20
 =20

The more I learn about the deli, the less I understand it. The deli is (was=
) of course Your Hometown Deli, a deli in Paulsboro, New Jersey, that  open=
ed in 2015 and  closed this August. During most of its seven-year run, Your=
 Hometown Deli was also the only business of a US public company called Hom=
etown International Inc., which means among (many) other things that you ca=
n  read its financial statements online. It had annual revenue that got as =
high as  $76,213 in 2016 (dollars in dollars) and as low as  $13,976 in 202=
0 (=E2=80=9CThe Company was forced to temporarily close the delicatessen du=
e to the stay-at-home order issued by the Governor of New Jersey on March 9=
, 2020, resulting from the outbreak of COVID-19.=E2=80=9D). It never manage=
d to turn a profit,
  [1]
=C2=A0but to be fair it is hard to pay the expenses of being a public compa=
ny =E2=80=94=C2=A0securities filings, audited financials, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0with five digits of revenue.=C2=A0
But the advantage of being a public company is that you have publicly trade=
d stock, and Hometown International did.
  [2]
=C2=A0In April 2021, hedge fund manager David Einhorn pointed out that (1) =
Hometown International=E2=80=99s equity market capitalization was over $113=
 million, (2) that was really weird and (3) =E2=80=9Cthe regulators =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0who are supposed to be protecting investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0appear =
to be neither present nor curious.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0We all  had a good  laugh =
about the deli, and the regulators noticed too. On Monday, the  US Securiti=
es and Exchange Commission and  federal prosecutors in New Jersey brought s=
ecurities fraud charges against three men involved in running the deli. Or,=
 rather, in running Hometown International, the publicly traded company. I =
don=E2=80=99t think they made the sandwiches.
What was the alleged fraud? Well, there are two basic shady things that you=
 can do with a ridiculous=C2=A0public company. One is a pump-and-dump.=C2=
=A0You print 10 million shares, you give them to yourself, you sell 100 of =
them to your buddy at $1 each, he sells those 100 shares back to you at $2 =
each, you sell them back to him at $4, he sells them back to you at $10, an=
d you can be like =E2=80=9Clook this company has a $100 million market cap =
and is up 900% this year!=E2=80=9D Then you post on some message boards abo=
ut how it has discovered a cure for cancer, or a revolutionary blockchain p=
roduct, or at least a delicious sandwich, and you try to get=C2=A0other=C2=
=A0people to buy the 10 million shares from you at $11 each. You use a comb=
ination of=C2=A0trading (wash trades with your buddy to make the stock go u=
p) and=C2=A0advertising=C2=A0to try to make the worthless stock look good a=
nd sell it to someone else.=C2=A0
This is straightforwardly illegal. The wash trading, and the lying about th=
e cancer/blockchain/sandwich, are very clearly securities fraud. There are =
obvious victims (the people who buy the stock from you), and you get in tro=
uble.
The other thing that you can do with a ridiculous public company is a=C2=A0=
reverse merger. You have a public company. It has just enough of a business=
 to=C2=A0be=C2=A0a public company: You sell some sandwiches, you have some =
revenue, you can write financial statements and get them audited, you can f=
ile a registration statement and quarterly disclosures with the SEC and the=
y=E2=80=99ll be like =E2=80=9Cyes, right, a deli, that=E2=80=99s a real bus=
iness.=E2=80=9D But it doesn=E2=80=99t have=C2=A0much=C2=A0of a business: T=
he deli brings in five figures of annual revenue and does not require a lot=
 of capital investment or research and development. From the SEC=E2=80=99s =
perspective it is a real=C2=A0or real-enough company; from your perspective=
 it is a=C2=A0shell=C2=A0company.
Then you find a private company (sometimes a foreign company) that would li=
ke to go public in the US and you negotiate a=C2=A0merger=C2=A0with that co=
mpany. The private company gets a public listing, without the expense and c=
omplication and regulatory attention=C2=A0of doing a full initial public of=
fering. You get some sort of commission for taking the company public on th=
e sly. It=E2=80=99s a little like a SPAC, a special purpose acquisition com=
pany, in that it is a shell company to be used to take another company publ=
ic, though SPACs have a lot more procedures and safeguards. Oh and then aft=
er the merger the company probably gets rid of the deli. The deli was just =
a placeholder, to make the shell company look less like a shell.
This is the sort of thing that can get you in trouble in various ways, and =
it is often=C2=A0accompanied=C2=A0by other sorts of shadiness (in particula=
r, the private company you merge with might have a good reason for wanting =
to avoid the regulatory review of an IPO), and you should certainly consult=
 a lawyer before=C2=A0doing=C2=A0it, but it is not=C2=A0obviously=C2=A0ille=
gal like the pump-and-dump is. You can sort of fall into it by accident: Yo=
u can start a real business, and take it public hoping to grow, and then it=
 fails, and you have a limping defunct business and a public listing, and s=
ome broker calls you up and says =E2=80=9Chey would you like to merge with =
an exciting private company, we=E2=80=99ll pay you, and it=E2=80=99s not li=
ke you=E2=80=99re really using your private listing,=E2=80=9D and you say s=
ure, whatever. It=E2=80=99s not illegal to have a public company that doesn=
=E2=80=99t do much, or to merge that company with another company that plan=
s to do more. If your disclosures are all accurate and complete then=C2=A0i=
t=E2=80=99s =E2=80=A6=C2=A0fine =E2=80=A6=C2=A0ish? Not legal advice.
As it happens, the deli=E2=80=99s biggest investor, Manoj Jain of Maso Capi=
tal Investments Ltd. in Hong Kong,  talked to the Financial Times last year=
 and said exactly that: It was a shell company designed to take an Asian pr=
ivate company public in the US. He explained in=C2=A0detail:

=E2=80=9CThe concept of shell companies has existed globally for many years=
,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThese are broadly quasi-dormant public compani=
es, that can be used to merge with private companies quickly and easily.=E2=
=80=9D
According to Jain, repurposing an existing business for M&A is an efficient=
 way to extend the Spac model to smaller deals. =E2=80=9CThe target compani=
es we=E2=80=99re speaking to are in the $300m to $600m zip code in terms of=
 valuation,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CTo get it to work from a public mark=
et perspective, the Spac needs to be $75m to $100m.=E2=80=9D
Yet setting up a Spac can cost millions of dollars in administration fees a=
