In 1948, the US Securities and Exchange Commission published Rule 17a-4(b),=
 which required regulated brokers to keep =E2=80=9Coriginals of all communi=
cations received and copies of all communications sent by such member, brok=
er or dealer (including inter-office memoranda and communications) relating=
 to his business as such.=E2=80=9D You can find the current version of the =
rule online  here, but you can also find the 1948 original online  here, an=
d even on the internet it is pleasingly yellowed. The rule has changed a bi=
t in the ensuing decades, but not too much.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CHis business=E2=
=80=9D is now =E2=80=9Cits business,=E2=80=9D because brokers are no longer=
 assumed to be=C2=A0male, though they=C2=A0are=C2=A0now assumed to be=C2=A0=
corporations, and an added sentence notes that =E2=80=9Ccommunications incl=
udes sales scripts and recordings of telephone calls required to be maintai=
ned=E2=80=9D by  other rules.=C2=A0But the basics are still the same. =E2=
=80=9CInter-office memoranda=E2=80=9D are still in the rule.
In 1948, if you were a broker, you probably communicated with your coworker=
s in roughly three ways:
=09Inter-office memoranda, for quite formal occasions. For new office polic=
ies, formal write-ups of investment ideas, etc., you=E2=80=99d spring for t=
he typewriter ribbons and carbon paper.=09Telephone. If your coworkers work=
ed in a different branch office, you might spring for a long-distance call =
to talk about urgent matters.=09Walking over to their desk and talking to t=
hem, would probably be the main form of communication.

So when the SEC said that brokers needed to keep copies of their business c=
orrespondence, that implicitly assumed a certain level of formality. The SE=
C might plausibly come to a broker in 1948 and say =E2=80=9Cshow me all of =
your internal communications for the last two years,=E2=80=9D and he (he) m=
ight hand the SEC, like, 30 memos, and the SEC might say =E2=80=9Cah right =
that=E2=80=99s a reasonable number of memos=E2=80=9D and then go read them.
One thing that has happened in the intervening 74 years is that written com=
munication has become much much much much much much much easier and more ca=
sual. I used to work on a desk at Goldman Sachs Group Inc., where the defau=
lt method of communication with someone who sat=C2=A0two=C2=A0seats away fr=
om you was instant messaging.
  [8]
=C2=A0There were some mornings when I sent more than 100 inter-office memor=
anda, though like 20 of them would be =E2=80=9Clol=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cfml=
.=E2=80=9D
  [9]

And so then if the SEC thought that a broker was up to no good, it could sa=
y =E2=80=9Cgive me all of the internal communications of one particular des=
k for the month of September,=E2=80=9D and the broker would hand over like =
500,000 emails and instant messages, and the SEC would run some search term=
s on this vast corpus, and the search terms would be like =E2=80=9Cfraud=E2=
=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cspoof=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cmanipulate=E2=80=9D and =E2=
=80=9Csucker=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cfml,=E2=80=9D and they=E2=80=99d get a h=
it like =E2=80=9Cfml i just did a fraud oops=E2=80=9D and go from there to =
build a case. In 1948, it would be=C2=A0very weird=C2=A0for a broker to sen=
d around an inter-office memo with the subject line =E2=80=9CRe: We need to=
 do more fraud.=E2=80=9D He might say it, but only out loud, in person, in =
a form not required to be preserved for SEC examination.=C2=A0By 2011, it w=
as just expected that if a broker was doing fraud there would be dozens of =
eternally preserved electronic messages about it.
In 2015,  Dan Davies wrote about a wave of foreign exchange manipulation sc=
andals:

It has been, in fact, a golden age of fraud detection.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 Elect=
ronic systems have played a role in uncovering all the big financial scanda=
ls of the past few years: the rigging of interest rate benchmarks, the effo=
rts of some banks to facilitate tax evasion and money laundering, and the p=
re-crisis fraud connected to sliced-and-diced mortgage debt. Look at that r=
ap sheet, and you might conclude that we have been through a period in whic=
h conduct in the banking industry was uniquely bad. Yet it may merely have =
been a period when, for the first time, bad actors in the financial sector =
co-ordinated their dastardly activities using a system of text messages tha=
t could be automatically searched. =E2=80=A6
For the past 10 years, traders have inadvertently made wrongdoing by people=
 in their ranks as easy as possible to detect. Is it any wonder so much has=
 been detected? ...
But the golden age is coming to an end. Nobody, after reading the transcrip=
ts =E2=80=94 the =E2=80=9Cbottle of Bolly=E2=80=9D for a nefarious trade, t=
he =E2=80=9CDone for you big boy=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 can fail to understand =
that online chats, however furtive and informal, are archived official comm=
unications.

This strikes me as a correct and important analysis of the modern golden ag=
e of fraud detection, though it turned out not to be a=C2=A0great predictio=
n. Intellectually people are broadly aware that online chats are archived f=
orever. Emotionally they love writing about fraud in the chat.
And then there was Covid-19. If you sit on a desk in an office, and you wan=
t to do fraud, you will=C2=A0probably=C2=A0type some instant messages about=
 it, because the temptation is almost irresistible. But you=C2=A0might=C2=
=A0instead just turn to your coworkers and say =E2=80=9Cahahaha I=E2=80=99m=
 doing so much fraud, high five=E2=80=9D and they might physically high-fiv=
e you instead of sending you a thumbs-up emoji in the chat. And then your c=
onfession, and their high-fives, will not be recorded for posterity. This m=
ight be best practices or, you know, second-best practices; not legal advic=
e. But then Covid-19 hit and everyone worked from home and so electronic ch=
ats became even more dominant.
If this is your model, you might have some sort of casual inchoate thought =
process that is like: Yes, fine, I will use my firm email address or my Blo=
omberg chat for=C2=A0official business, things that would have been inter-o=
ffice memoranda in 1948, but when I am=C2=A0just chatting I will use, you k=
now, Snap or WhatsApp or Signal or texts from my personal cell phone. Inclu=
ding when I am=C2=A0just chatting=C2=A0with my colleagues or my clients. In=
cluding when I am just chatting=C2=A0with them=C2=A0about business. We=E2=
=80=99ll talk about stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0about trades, about business, abou=
t desk politics =E2=80=94=C2=A0informally, like we would in person, over so=
me sort of unofficial messaging platform. And then maybe if there=E2=80=99s=
 a trade to be done or a policy to be made or whatever, we will formalize i=
t in an email. But the SEC rule about preserving communications doesn=E2=80=
=99t apply to=C2=A0talking to my coworkers in person, and so it shouldn=E2=
=80=99t apply to things that are=C2=A0like that. So if there=E2=80=99s some=
thing I want to say to them in person, but that is inconvenient =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0because we are working from home, or because we are both in the offic=
e but I=E2=80=99d have to stand up and walk two seats over to talk to them =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0then I=E2=80=99ll just put in in my personal WhatsApp and th=
at=E2=80=99s fine.
That is not fine,   it turns out:

US regulators reached settlements with a dozen banks in a sprawling probe i=
nto how global financial firms failed to monitor employees=E2=80=99 communi=
cations on unauthorized messaging apps, bringing total penalties in the mat=
ter to more than $2 billion.=C2=A0
The Securities and Exchange Commission announced $1.1 billion in fines and =
the Commodity Futures Trading Commission disclosed $710 million in penaltie=
s in separate statements Tuesday. Those levies -- against firms including B=
ank of America Corp., Citigroup Inc. and Goldman Sachs Group Inc. -- combin=
ed with JPMorgan Chase & Co.=E2=80=99s $200 million in fines from December,=
 bring the total to $2.01 billion, making them the biggest penalties ever a=
gainst US banks for record-keeping lapses.=C2=A0

Here are the  SEC and  CFTC releases. The SEC one is pretty undifferentiate=
d: Eight big firms agreed to pay $125 million each, with three other smalle=
r firms=C2=A0paying a bit less. (The CFTC one is pretty similar =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the big banks paid $75 million each =E2=80=94=C2=A0except that Bank o=
f America Corp. is paying $100 million because the head of one of its tradi=
ng desks was constantly  going around telling people to delete messages, wh=
ich the CFTC didn=E2=80=99t like.)=C2=A0
The message of the fines is that every bank did more or less the same thing=
 and there are no gradations of culpability. On the one hand, every bank ha=
d lots of employees who used WhatsApp or personal cell phones to communicat=
e about work, and there is no real point in quantifying how many. On the ot=
her hand, the SEC=E2=80=99s review of sample communications on those channe=
ls does not seem to have turned up any=C2=A0crimes. These people used perso=
nal cell phones to talk about work, not because they were doing crimes that=
 they wanted to hide from the authorities, but because their personal cell =
phones felt more convenient or more personal or more like in-person chattin=
g than official email did.
The SEC=E2=80=99s statements are so weird:
=E2=80=9CToday=E2=80=99s actions =E2=80=93 both in terms of the firms invol=
ved and the size of the penalties ordered =E2=80=93 underscore the importan=
ce of recordkeeping requirements: they=E2=80=99re sacrosanct. If there are =
allegations of wrongdoing or misconduct, we must be able to examine a firm=
=E2=80=99s books and records to determine what happened,=E2=80=9D said Gurb=
ir S. Grewal, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement. =E2=80=
=9CThese 16 firms not only have admitted the facts and acknowledged that th=
eir conduct violated these very important requirements, but have also start=
ed to implement measures to prevent future violations. Other broker dealers=
 and asset managers who are subject to similar requirements under the feder=
al securities laws would be well-served to self-report and self-remediate a=
ny deficiencies.=E2=80=9D
No look if you announce that every big bank paid the exact same fine for sy=
stematically ignoring these requirements, that does=C2=A0not=C2=A0underscor=
e that those requirements are sacrosanct. If they were sacrosanct, one bank=
=C2=A0might have followed them.
  [10]
 And:
=E2=80=9CFinance, ultimately, depends on trust. By failing to honor their r=
ecordkeeping and books-and-records obligations, the market participants we =
have charged today have failed to maintain that trust,=E2=80=9D said SEC Ch=
air Gary Gensler. =E2=80=9CSince the 1930s, such recordkeeping has been vit=
al to preserve market integrity. As technology changes, it=E2=80=99s even m=
ore important that registrants appropriately conduct their communications a=
bout business matters within only official channels, and they must maintain=
 and preserve those communications.=E2=80=9D
My point here is that when these rules were written, it would have been abs=
urd to say that brokers had to =E2=80=9Cappropriately conduct their communi=
cations about business matters within only official channels.=E2=80=9D Ever=
yone understood, in 1948, that only a small sliver of business was conducte=
d in formal letters and memoranda, and that mostly you=E2=80=99d talk about=
 business face-to-face. =E2=80=9CAs technology changes,=E2=80=9D lots of fo=
rms of written electronic communication become substitutes=C2=A0not for mem=
oranda, but for face-to-face conversation. So the SEC=E2=80=99s requirement=
s constantly become=C2=A0broader. If you just talk to your colleagues in pe=
rson, the SEC does not expect you to preserve that. Once you move that chat=
 to WhatsApp, it does.

