   =20
      David Solomon hobby update
   =20
 =20

When David Solomon became the chief executive officer of Goldman Sachs Grou=
p Inc., he and Goldman did a lot of public relations around the fact that h=
e also likes to DJ. Part of the purpose of this, I guess, was to suggest th=
at Solomon is cool and young and with-it? But part of it was to suggest tha=
t Solomon was an outsider, not a traditional banker, who had to overcome ad=
versity on his way to the top. The adversity of crusty old traditional bank=
ers saying =E2=80=9CDavid, you have talent, but you=E2=80=99ll never become=
 CEO of Goldman if you keep DJing.=E2=80=9D From a  2019 profile in Fortune=
:
Solomon was outed as DJ D-Sol by the New York Times in 2017, when he was st=
ill one of two copresidents gunning for the top job at the firm. Known at t=
he office as an =C3=BCber-professional, hard-charging manager with little p=
atience for small talk, Solomon was anxious that people would no longer tak=
e him seriously=E2=80=94mistakenly equating the side gig with some sort of =
midlife crisis. Some advisers told him to hang it up. =E2=80=9CI thought fo=
r a minute, Well, can I do this, can I not do this?=E2=80=9D recalls Solomo=
n, who donates the proceeds from his gigs and Spotify plays to drug-addicti=
on-related philanthropies. (He says the total he has raised is in the six f=
igures.) Those doubts soon dispersed, especially after his boss at the time=
, then-CEO Lloyd Blankfein, and others endorsed it. =E2=80=9CYou know what,=
 it=E2=80=99s who I am, and nobody would tell me not to play golf,=E2=80=9D=
 Solomon says now. =E2=80=9CAnd why shouldn=E2=80=99t I=E2=80=94because I=
=E2=80=99m a CEO?=E2=80=9D
Yes! It=E2=80=99s a feel-good story of a scrappy outsider who shocked the o=
ld guard by DJing=C2=A0instead of golfing, and who nonetheless managed to r=
ise to the top.
Well. Here=E2=80=99s  an Insider article=C2=A0from last week about how =E2=
=80=9CGoldman Sachs insiders are fuming over their CEO=E2=80=99s use of pri=
vate jets to promote his side hustle as a DJ,=E2=80=9D and more generally t=
hat there are worries at Goldman that Solomon might be placing his personal=
 brand (as a DJ and thought leader) over the firm. But there is also this:
Solomon has recently been working on his golf game and has sought out membe=
rships at some of the country's most prestigious golf clubs and courses, so=
urces said. The CEO is a member of The Bridge, which The New York Times onc=
e described as "casual chic" with a clubhouse that was "glassy and aggressi=
vely futuristic" and looked "more like a contemporary art museum in Berlin.=
"
Now that he=E2=80=99s been the CEO for a while he=E2=80=99s allowed to golf=
 too.

