!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> federal prosecutors describe=
</a> the alleged fraud at the deli (and another similarly shell-y company c=
alled E-Waste Corp. that was allegedly controlled by the same people):</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Patten, Coker Sr., and Coker Jr. took steps to=
 gain control of both entities=E2=80=99 management and stock with the ultim=
ate intention of entering reverse mergers, a transaction through which an e=
xisting public company merges with a private operating company. A successfu=
l reverse merger =C2=A0would allow the defendants to sell shares of each en=
tity at a significant profit.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In or around 2014, two New Jersey residents be=
gan the process of opening a local deli in Paulsboro, New Jersey. One of th=
e individuals discussed his interest in opening the deli with Patten, a lon=
g-time friend, who suggested the creation of Hometown International, an umb=
rella corporation, under which the deli would operate as a wholly owned sub=
sidiary. Unbeknownst to the deli owners, almost immediately after Hometown =
International was formed, Patten and his associates began positioning Homet=
own International as a vehicle for a reverse merger that would yield substa=
ntial profit to them. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Once the defendants gained control of Hometown=
 International and E-Waste=E2=80=99s shares, they arranged for the transfer=
 of millions of shares of stock to a number of nominee entities, including =
entities controlled by Coker Jr., in an effort to mask their control of the=
 shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In addition, the defendants transferred shares=
 to family members, friends, and associates and gained control over their t=
rading accounts by obtaining their log-in information in order to conceal t=
he defendants=E2=80=99 involvement. The defendants then used those accounts=
 to commit a number of coordinated trading events, often referred to as mat=
ch and wash trades, to trade in Hometown International and E-Waste Corp.=E2=
=80=99s stock on both sides of the transaction.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These tactics artificially inflated the price =
of Hometown International and E-Waste=E2=80=99s stock by giving the false i=
mpression that there was a genuine market interest in the stock. Their sche=
me had the ultimate impact of artificially inflating Hometown International=
=E2=80=99s stock by approximately 939 percent and E-Waste=E2=80=99s stock b=
y approximately 19,900 percent.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the=C2=A0<em>point=C2=A0</em>was allegedly =
to do a reverse merger with a real company and then sell the shares at a pr=
ofit. And I suppose doing a reverse merger with a $100 million public compa=
ny is more appealing than doing one with a $100,000 public company, so they=
 allegedly used wash trading to inflate the stock. For instance, from <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMi9jb21wLXByMjAyMi0xNz=
IucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe23b9010" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the SEC=E2=80=99s compl=
aint</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For example, on November 19, 2020 =
at 9:50 a.m., a sale order was placed in an account in the name of =E2=80=
=9CA.B.,=E2=80=9D an associate of Patten. The order was placed from an IP a=
ddress associated with Patten. The following week, a buy order was placed i=
n the account of =E2=80=9CM.M.,=E2=80=9D also an associate of Patten, from =
the same IP address associated with Patten. The wash trade was immediately =
executed, resulting in an exchange of 200 shares at a price of $10.45 per s=
hare between one Patten-controlled account and another Patten-controlled ac=
count.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talk sometimes around here about US equity =
market structure, about spoofing, about high-frequency traders who race to =
buy stock a millisecond ahead of the competition. This guy put in an order =
to sell 200 shares=C2=A0on Thursday morning, Nov. 19, and then waited=C2=A0=
<em>six days=C2=A0</em>to put in a buy order for those 200 shares, and thos=
e orders traded with each other.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footno=
te-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !im=
portant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It is a more=C2=A0leisurely pace. Nobody traded any Hometown stoc=
k at all between Thursday, Nov. 19 and Wednesday, Nov. 25, when these 200 s=
hares crossed. Bloomberg tells me that those 200 shares are the only shares=
 that traded the whole week of Nov. 23. The whole month of November 2020, o=
nly 1,070 shares traded.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Were all of them wash trades among these alleg=
ed conspirators? Man, I don=E2=80=99t know, but would=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</e=
m>buy incredibly illiquid shares of a money-losing deli at a $100 million m=
arket cap? The reason that the SEC and prosecutors could find a bunch of ma=
tched trades, with the buys and sells minutes or hours or days apart, is th=
at no one was trading Hometown stock=C2=A0<em>except=C2=A0</em>these allege=
d conspirators. Or almost no one. The SEC does say:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">However, certain individual invest=
ors not associated with Defendants also purchased shares of Hometown Intern=
ational at the artificially inflated prices caused by Defendants=E2=80=99 f=
raud and, thus, have been injured.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It doesn=E2=80=99t say who though, or how many=
, or when. And there is no allegation at all that the defendants=C2=A0<em>t=
ried=C2=A0</em>to get anyone else to buy the stock. They were not pumping i=
t on message boards, telling people that Hometown had discovered the next g=
reat sandwich. They were just building up a market capitalization as an abs=
tract arithmetic object: If you have a company with <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvd=
i9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2MzIwODEvMDAwMTIxMzkwMDIwMDM1MjcwL2YxMHEwOTIw=
X2hvbWV0b3duLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa4221b5a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> 8 million sh=
ares</a>=C2=A0and two of your buddies trade 200 of them=C2=A0at $10.45, the=
n (1) one of your buddies has to send $2,090 to your other buddy and (2) yo=
u have an $83 million company, as a matter of the definition of =E2=80=9Cma=
rket capitalization.=E2=80=9D You can leverage $2,090 of real money =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0which you=E2=80=99re sending to yourself anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0int=
o $83 million of paper value.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What do you do with that paper value? I mean, =
reading between the lines, I gather that the answer is that you go to Manoj=
 Jain and you say =E2=80=9Chi, we have a $100 million-ish public company, w=
e hear that you have a $400 million-ish private company, let=E2=80=99s merg=
e, you=E2=80=99ll get a US public listing and we=E2=80=99ll get 20% of the =
combined company, in proportion to the value that we=E2=80=99re putting in.=
=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The value that you=E2=80=99re putting in is fake =E2=80=94=C2=A0y=
ou=E2=80=99ve got a small money-losing deli and some $2,000 wash trades =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but everything that we=E2=80=99re talking about here is pretty =
fake anyway so maybe it=E2=80=99s fine?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, the deli is famous =E2=80=94=C2=A0much mo=
re famous than E-Waste or=C2=A0other reverse-merger shell companies =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0largely because (1) it=E2=80=99s a deli, which is funny and (2) Da=
vid Einhorn called attention to it in his=C2=A0investor letter. This was in=
=C2=A0the glory days of meme stocks, and when Einhorn=E2=80=99s letter came=
 out on April 15, 2021, there=C2=A0was some suggestion that the deli was an=
other meme stock, another case of enthusiastic retail investors piling into=
 a charming company at an absurd valuation. It was not: Only about 1,781 sh=
ares of Hometown stock had traded between April 1 and April 14, for less th=
an $25,000 total.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgr=
ound-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Nobody was rushing to buy stock of the deli.=C2=A0<em>Until Einho=
rn made fun of it</em>. Hometown=E2=80=99s stock traded 42,762 shares the n=
ext day, April 16, and thousands more the=C2=A0next week, all at prices abo=
ve $12.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Your model here could be that some conspirator=
s were quietly wash trading Hometown stock back and forth for reasons of th=
eir own, not bothering anybody, and then Einhorn came along and said =E2=80=
=9Chey look at this absurdly=C2=A0overpriced stock,=E2=80=9D and a bunch of=
 retail investors were like =E2=80=9Cabsurdly overpriced stock? how do I ge=
t that,=E2=80=9D and so they rushed to buy. In a sense Einhorn helped execu=
te the pump-and-dump; like, the postmodern, 2021 way to do a pump-and-dump =
is<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tra=
nsparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Get control of a tiny stock.</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Wash trade it back and forth with your fri=
ends until the price is absurdly high.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">Go on message boards and say =E2=80=9CI am a fancy hedge fund manager =
and I have noticed that the price of this stock is absurdly high. For shame=
, retail apes!=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">All the re=
tail traders rush to buy it, because they don=E2=80=99t like hedge fund man=
agers and/or because it=E2=80=99s funny.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">Dump the stock on them.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said I don=E2=80=99t think that=E2=80=99s=
 what happened, and there's no allegation that the defendants actually=C2=
=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>dump any stock after Einhorn blew up their situation. =
Instead, says the SEC:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Despite this negative press, Defendants contin=
ued to endeavor to find a company to engage in a reverse merger with Hometo=
wn International so that they could change the name,=C2=A0ticker symbol, an=
d business operations of the issuer, in order to more easily dump their sha=
res at an artificially inflated price and further profit from their scheme.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a January 13, 2021 email between the Defend=
ants, Coker Jr. indicated that the Defendants=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Cstrategy=E2=
=80=9D was that the =E2=80=9Cannouncement of [a reverse merger] deal=E2=80=
=9D would lead to a =E2=80=9Cmassive=E2=80=9D increase in the trading volum=
e of the issuers, which would allow them to more easily dump their shares i=
nto the market. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a Form 8-K filed on March 31, 2022 and sign=
ed by Coker Jr., it was announced that Hometown International had entered i=
nto a merger agreement with a private Delaware corporation and that the com=
pany had changed its name with the State of Nevada from Hometown Internatio=
nal, Inc. to Makamer Holdings, Inc.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On April 1, 2022, the reverse merger was compl=
eted, with Hometown International acquiring Makamer Holdings, but operating=
 under the name Makamer Holdings. That same day, Coker Jr. was replaced as =
Chief Executive Officer by Makamer Holdings=E2=80=99 President. In the reve=
rse merger, the stockholders of Makamer Holdings exchanged shares of Makame=
r Holdings common stock for shares of Hometown International, and thus the =
Defendants retained the shares of Hometown International stock that they ha=
d acquired in connection with their fraud. In approximately August 2022, FI=
NRA issued a deficiency letter to Hometown International, effectively rejec=
ting the issuer=E2=80=99s request to change its name and ticker symbol, and=
 thus the stock still trades under the Hometown International ticker symbol=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">(Also during this period, the actual deli foun=
der =E2=80=94=C2=A0Paulsboro high school wrestling coach Paul Morina =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0seems to have gotten freaked out and =E2=80=9Craised significant c=
oncerns with Patten regarding the negative news,=E2=80=9D at which point he=
 was <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.2675=
34/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2MzIwODEvMDAwMTIx=
MzkwMDIxMDI2NTA2L2VhMTQwOTQxLThrX2hvbWV0b3duaW50bC5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB31be0569" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> removed as chief executive officer of the public c=
ompany</a>, though he kept running the deli.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The merger=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9k=
b2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTYzMjA4MS8wMDAxMjEzOTAwMjIwMTY4OTAvZWExNTc=
3NDUtOGtfbWFrYW1lci5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC4a1e62ef" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> 8-K</a=
> says that Makamer got 30 million shares; Hometown=E2=80=99s existing shar=
eholders got about 6.3 million.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !imp=
ortant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know how much Makamer is worth =E2=80=94 Bloomber=
g shows its current equity market cap as $216 million, but it has traded an=
 average of 94 shares a day since the merger, so who knows =E2=80=94=C2=A0b=
ut you can see the rough idea working. The Hometown promoters got 17% of th=
e value of a=C2=A0company in exchange for giving it a public shell.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0<em>obvious=C2=A0</e=
m>that 17% of Makamer is all that valuable. Its revenue is even lower than =
the deli=E2=80=99s, in that it is zero.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9k=
b2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTYzMjA4MS8wMDAxMjEzOTAwMjIwNDc1NDYvZjEwcTA=
2MjJfbWFrYW1lci5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cDe34c6b70" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Makamer</a=
> =E2=80=9Cwas organized on September 3, 2021, to develop and market biodeg=
radable resins with the goal of replacing traditional plastics with renewab=
le and compostable materials to help reduce worldwide toxic plastic waste p=
ollution,=E2=80=9D but there is not exactly a ton of public information=C2=
=A0about how it plans to do that. One shady way to do shell company reverse=
 mergers is to do them <em>repeatedly</em>: You have a shell company with a=
 basically nonexistent business, it trades publicly, you merge with some pr=
ivate business that is also basically nonexistent, you see if anyone wants =
to buy=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>stock, if they do, great, you sell some, and=
 then it crashes and you do another merger and try again.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The market did not particularly react to Homet=
own=E2=80=99s merger with Makamer, though:=C2=A0Bloomberg data shows that i=
t traded a total of 503 shares in the=C2=A0<em>month=C2=A0</em>between the =
merger announcement and closing, and another=C2=A0<em>one=C2=A0</em>share i=
n the=C2=A0<em>month=C2=A0</em>after closing. And the <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGl=
jZS5nb3YvdXNhby1uai9wcmVzcy1yZWxlYXNlL2ZpbGUvMTUzODAzMS9kb3dubG9hZA/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB54358108" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> criminal indictment</a> adds that =E2=
=80=9CPATTEN, COKER, SR., and COKER, JR. have not yet sold shares of Hometo=
wn International for a profit.=E2=80=9D The deli=E2=80=99s notoriety, and t=
he ensuing regulatory attention =E2=80=94=C2=A0Finra refused to change the =
ticker, and OTC Markets, where the stock trades, <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cub3RjbWFya2V0=
cy5jb20vc3RvY2svSFdJTi9vdmVydmlldw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBda3746d5" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> has a skull and crossbones on the quote</a> =E2=80=94 make it hard to d=
ump the stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, the defendants have made so=
me money. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2920=
1598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMi9=
jb21wLXByMjAyMi0xNzIucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCe23b9010" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> SEC n=
otes</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On April 14, 2020, Hometown International and =
three investors located in Hong Kong consummated a private placement, orche=
strated by Defendants, in which Hometown International transferred 2.5 mill=
ion shares of stock for $2.5 million. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the weeks following the infusion of $2.5 mi=
llion into the Hometown International checking account, Patten transferred =
more than $534,000 out of the account to Coker Sr. and Coker Jr.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This money was paid under =E2=80=9Cconsulting =
agreements,=E2=80=9D and the SEC says that =E2=80=9Cany =E2=80=98services=
=E2=80=99 in connection with the purported consulting agreements were unnec=
essary, not performed, or were in furtherance of the scheme.=E2=80=9D But =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0where did the money come from? The Hong Kong investors who p=
aid $2.5 million are never named, either in the charging documents or in <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2MzIwODEvMDAwMTIxMzkwMDI=
wMDA5NDU5L2VhMTIwNzY4LThrX2hvbWV0b3duLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb3321d=
48" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> Hometown=E2=80=99s own filings</a>, but Bloomberg shows that =
the top holder of Hometown stock is Maso Capital Partners Ltd., which owns =
2.5 million shares through three different funds, and whose manager I quote=
d above talking about using shell companies as a route to the public market=
s. It seems reasonable to think that Maso put in $2.5 million=C2=A0<em>to b=
e able to use the shell company</em>, not to finance the deli=E2=80=99s ope=
rations, and that=C2=A0<em>of course=C2=A0</em>that $2.5 million was suppos=
ed to be paid out to the promoters of the shell. The deli had nothing to do=
 with it; that was a $2.5 million payment from a shell-company intermediary=
 (Maso) to some shell-company suppliers (Patten et al.).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Did =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0work? I g=
uess that is the main thing I don=E2=80=99t understand about the deli. They=
 succeeded in turning a small money-losing deli into a public company with =
a $100 million paper valuation, and then merging that public company with a=
nother company at an even higher valuation, which I think is most of the pl=
an. But, except for the week after David Einhorn made fun of them, they don=
=E2=80=99t seem to have succeeded in actually selling any of this stock to =
anyone (except Maso?). One possibility is that this was all entirely ill-co=
nceived and they never would have. Another possibility is that the publicit=
y Einhorn brought to the deli made it impossible for the plan to succeed, a=
nd the regulators have been toying with them ever since, sure that they=E2=
=80=99d never actually manage to dump their stock on the public.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know! The poor deli guy. He ju=
st wanted to start a deli. His <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAyMi8wOS8yNy8xMD=
AtbWlsbGlvbi1uZXctamVyc2V5LWRlbGktc2NhbS1mZWRzLXNvdWdodC10by1qYWlsLWZhdGhlc=
i13aGlsZS1zb24taXMtYXQtbGFyZ2UuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC80f974c5" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> high school wrestling buddy</a>, Patten, was a sophisticated financi=
er, so he discussed his deli plans with him. And if you believe these alleg=
ations, his friend was=C2=A0like =E2=80=9Cwell what you do is you get a pub=
lic-company shell and you operate the deli as a subsidiary of the shell unt=
il I can sell the shell to international financial interests to use to take=
 other dodgy companies public, at which point I will get a bunch of shares =
to dump on the unsuspecting public, and you=E2=80=99ll get your deli back.=
=E2=80=9D Just start the deli! The moral of the story might be that if you =
want to start a small local business you should not ask your international =
financier friends for advice.</p>
