<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Texting</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 1948, the US Securities and Exchange Commis=
sion published Rule 17a-4(b), which required regulated brokers to keep =E2=
=80=9Coriginals of all communications received and copies of all communicat=
ions sent by such member, broker or dealer (including inter-office memorand=
a and communications) relating to his business as such.=E2=80=9D You can fi=
nd the current version of the rule online <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR=
1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4xN2EtNA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB13cad139" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 here</a>, but you can also find the 1948 original online <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29=
2aW5mby5nb3YvY29udGVudC9wa2cvRlItMTk0OC0xMi0yMi9wZGYvRlItMTk0OC0xMi0yMi5wZG=
YjcGFnZT0x/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB703b721f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here</a>, and even o=
n the internet it is pleasingly yellowed. The rule has changed a bit in the=
 ensuing decades, but not too much.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CHis business=E2=80=9D is =
now =E2=80=9Cits business,=E2=80=9D because brokers are no longer assumed t=
o be=C2=A0male, though they=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>now assumed to be=C2=A0c=
orporations, and an added sentence notes that =E2=80=9Ccommunications inclu=
des sales scripts and recordings of telephone calls required to be maintain=
ed=E2=80=9D by <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/292=
01598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L3VzY29kZS90ZXh0LzE1Lzc4by=
0xMA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB54ad443d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> other rules</a>.=C2=A0But =
the basics are still the same. =E2=80=9CInter-office memoranda=E2=80=9D are=
 still in the rule.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 1948, if you were a broker, you probably co=
mmunicated with your coworkers in roughly three ways:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Inter-office memoranda, for quite for=
mal occasions. For new office policies, formal write-ups of investment idea=
s, etc., you=E2=80=99d spring for the typewriter ribbons and carbon paper.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Telephone. If your coworkers worke=
d in a different branch office, you might spring for a long-distance call t=
o talk about urgent matters.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Walki=
ng over to their desk and talking to them, would probably be the main form =
of communication.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So when the SEC said that brokers needed to ke=
ep copies of their business correspondence, that implicitly assumed a certa=
in level of formality. The SEC might plausibly come to a broker in 1948 and=
 say =E2=80=9Cshow me all of your internal communications for the last two =
years,=E2=80=9D and he (he) might hand the SEC, like, 30 memos, and the SEC=
 might say =E2=80=9Cah right that=E2=80=99s a reasonable number of memos=E2=
=80=9D and then go read them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing that has happened in the intervening=
 74 years is that written communication has become much much much much much=
 much much easier and more casual. I used to work on a desk at Goldman Sach=
s Group Inc., where the default method of communication with someone who sa=
t=C2=A0<em>two=C2=A0</em>seats away from you was instant messaging.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0There were some mornings when I sent more than 100 inter-office m=
emoranda, though like 20 of them would be =E2=80=9Clol=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9Cfml.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so then if the SEC thought that a broker w=
as up to no good, it could say =E2=80=9Cgive me all of the internal communi=
cations of one particular desk for the month of September,=E2=80=9D and the=
 broker would hand over like 500,000 emails and instant messages, and the S=
EC would run some search terms on this vast corpus, and the search terms wo=
uld be like =E2=80=9Cfraud=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cspoof=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=
=9Cmanipulate=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Csucker=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cfml,=E2=80=
=9D and they=E2=80=99d get a hit like =E2=80=9Cfml i just did a fraud oops=
=E2=80=9D and go from there to build a case. In 1948, it would be=C2=A0<em>=
very weird=C2=A0</em>for a broker to send around an inter-office memo with =
the subject line =E2=80=9CRe: We need to do more fraud.=E2=80=9D He might <=
em>say </em>it, but only out loud, in person, in a form not required to be =
preserved for SEC examination.=C2=A0By 2011, it was just expected that if a=
 broker was doing fraud there would be dozens of eternally preserved electr=
onic messages about it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2015, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMGN=
mZTk2NGEtMDA2ZS0xMWU1LWE5MDgtMDAxNDRmZWFiZGMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB004b=
aa4f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> Dan Davies wrote</a> about a wave of foreign exchange manipu=
lation scandals:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It has been, in fact, a golden age of fraud de=
tection.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 Electronic systems have played a role in uncovering=
 all the big financial scandals of the past few years: the rigging of inter=
est rate benchmarks, the efforts of some banks to facilitate tax evasion an=
d money laundering, and the pre-crisis fraud connected to sliced-and-diced =
mortgage debt. Look at that rap sheet, and you might conclude that we have =
been through a period in which conduct in the banking industry was uniquely=
 bad. Yet it may merely have been a period when, for the first time, bad ac=
tors in the financial sector co-ordinated their dastardly activities using =
a system of text messages that could be automatically searched. =E2=80=A6</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For the past 10 years, traders have inadverten=
tly made wrongdoing by people in their ranks as easy as possible to detect.=
 Is it any wonder so much has been detected? ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the golden age is coming to an end. Nobody=
, after reading the transcripts =E2=80=94 the =E2=80=9Cbottle of Bolly=E2=
=80=9D for a nefarious trade, the =E2=80=9CDone for you big boy=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94 can fail to understand that online chats, however furtive and inf=
ormal, are archived official communications.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This strikes me as a correct and important ana=
lysis of the modern golden age of fraud detection, though it turned out not=
 to be a=C2=A0great prediction. Intellectually people are broadly aware tha=
t online chats are archived forever. Emotionally they love writing about fr=
aud in the chat.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then there was Covid-19. If you sit on a d=
esk in an office, and you want to do fraud, you will=C2=A0<em>probably=C2=
=A0</em>type some instant messages about it, because the temptation is almo=
st irresistible. But you=C2=A0<em>might=C2=A0</em>instead just turn to your=
 coworkers and say =E2=80=9Cahahaha I=E2=80=99m doing so much fraud, high f=
ive=E2=80=9D and they might physically high-five you instead of sending you=
 a thumbs-up emoji in the chat. And then your confession, and their high-fi=
ves, will not be recorded for posterity. This might be best practices or, y=
ou know, second-best practices; not legal advice. But then Covid-19 hit and=
 everyone worked from home and so electronic chats became even more dominan=
t.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If this is your model, you might have some sor=
t of casual inchoate thought process that is like: Yes, fine, I will use my=
 firm email address or my Bloomberg chat for=C2=A0<em>official business</em=
>, things that would have been inter-office memoranda in 1948, but when I a=
m=C2=A0<em>just chatting </em>I will use, you know, Snap or WhatsApp or Sig=
nal or texts from my personal cell phone. Including when I am=C2=A0<em>just=
 chatting=C2=A0</em>with my colleagues or my clients. Including when I am <=
em>just chatting=C2=A0</em>with them=C2=A0<em>about business</em>. We=E2=80=
=99ll talk about stuff =E2=80=94=C2=A0about trades, about business, about d=
esk politics =E2=80=94=C2=A0informally, like we would in person, over some =
sort of unofficial messaging platform. And then maybe if there=E2=80=99s a =
trade to be done or a policy to be made or whatever, we will formalize it i=
n an email. But the SEC rule about preserving communications doesn=E2=80=99=
t apply to=C2=A0<em>talking to my coworkers in person</em>, and so it <em>s=
houldn=E2=80=99t</em> apply to things that are=C2=A0<em>like that</em>. So =
if there=E2=80=99s something I want to say to them in person, but that is i=
nconvenient =E2=80=94=C2=A0because we are working from home, or because we =
are both in the office but I=E2=80=99d have to stand up and walk two seats =
over to talk to them =E2=80=94=C2=A0then I=E2=80=99ll just put in in my per=
sonal WhatsApp and that=E2=80=99s fine.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is not fine, <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMjcvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtd2hhdHNhcHAtcHJvYmUtc=
G9pc2VkLXRvLXJlc3VsdC1pbi1oaXN0b3JpYy1maW5lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA5MjgyMl9NT05FWVNU=
VUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDk=
yOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfdfbfc83" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  it turns out</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US regulators reached settlements with a dozen=
 banks in a sprawling probe into how global financial firms failed to monit=
or employees=E2=80=99 communications on unauthorized messaging apps, bringi=
ng total penalties in the matter to more than $2 billion.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission announc=
ed $1.1 billion in fines and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission discl=
osed $710 million in penalties in separate statements Tuesday. Those levies=
 -- against firms including Bank of America Corp., Citigroup Inc. and Goldm=
an Sachs Group Inc. -- combined with JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co.=E2=80=99s $20=
0 million in fines from December, bring the total to $2.01 billion, making =
them the biggest penalties ever against US banks for record-keeping lapses.=
=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3B=
yZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi0xNzQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB059e3f92" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> SE=
C</a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598=
.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1ByZXNzUmVsZWFzZXMvODU5OS0=
yMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc9fe26fd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> CFTC</a> releases. The SEC =
one is pretty undifferentiated: Eight big firms agreed to pay $125 million =
each, with three other smaller firms=C2=A0paying a bit less. (The CFTC one =
is pretty similar =E2=80=94=C2=A0the big banks paid $75 million each =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0except that Bank of America Corp. is paying $100 million because t=
he head of one of its trading desks was constantly <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29201598.267534/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3=
YvbWVkaWEvNzcyMS9lbmZiYW5rb2ZhbWVyaWNhb3JkZXIwOTI3MjIvZG93bmxvYWQ/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB8938745b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> going around telling people to delete me=
ssages</a>, which the CFTC didn=E2=80=99t like.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The message of the fines is that every bank di=
d more or less the same thing and there are no gradations of culpability. O=
n the one hand, every bank had lots of employees who used WhatsApp or perso=
nal cell phones to communicate about work, and there is no real point in qu=
antifying how many. On the other hand, the SEC=E2=80=99s review of sample c=
ommunications on those channels does not seem to have turned up any=C2=A0<e=
m>crimes</em>. These people used personal cell phones to talk about work, n=
ot because they were doing crimes that they wanted to hide from the authori=
ties, but because their personal cell phones felt more convenient or more p=
ersonal or more like in-person chatting than official email did.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s statements are so weird:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CToday=E2=80=99s actions =
=E2=80=93 both in terms of the firms involved and the size of the penalties=
 ordered =E2=80=93 underscore the importance of recordkeeping requirements:=
 they=E2=80=99re sacrosanct. If there are allegations of wrongdoing or misc=
onduct, we must be able to examine a firm=E2=80=99s books and records to de=
termine what happened,=E2=80=9D said Gurbir S. Grewal, Director of the SEC=
=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement. =E2=80=9CThese 16 firms not only have a=
dmitted the facts and acknowledged that their conduct violated these very i=
mportant requirements, but have also started to implement measures to preve=
nt future violations. Other broker dealers and asset managers who are subje=
ct to similar requirements under the federal securities laws would be well-=
served to self-report and self-remediate any deficiencies.=E2=80=9D</p></bl=
ockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No look if you announce that every big bank pa=
id the exact same fine for systematically ignoring these requirements, that=
 does=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>underscore that those requirements are sacrosa=
nct. If they were sacrosanct, <em>one bank=C2=A0</em>might have followed th=
em.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: t=
ransparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a> And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CFinance, ultimately, depe=
nds on trust. By failing to honor their recordkeeping and books-and-records=
 obligations, the market participants we have charged today have failed to =
maintain that trust,=E2=80=9D said SEC Chair Gary Gensler. =E2=80=9CSince t=
he 1930s, such recordkeeping has been vital to preserve market integrity. A=
s technology changes, it=E2=80=99s even more important that registrants app=
ropriately conduct their communications about business matters within only =
official channels, and they must maintain and preserve those communications=
.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My point here is that when these rules were wr=
itten, it would have been absurd to say that brokers had to =E2=80=9Capprop=
riately conduct their communications about business matters within only off=
icial channels.=E2=80=9D Everyone understood, in 1948, that only a small sl=
iver of business was conducted in formal letters and memoranda, and that mo=
stly you=E2=80=99d talk about business face-to-face. =E2=80=9CAs technology=
 changes,=E2=80=9D lots of forms of written electronic communication become=
 substitutes=C2=A0<em>not for memoranda, but for face-to-face conversation<=
/em>. So the SEC=E2=80=99s requirements constantly become=C2=A0<em>broader<=
/em>. If you just talk to your colleagues in person, the SEC does not expec=
t you to preserve that. Once you move that chat to WhatsApp, it does.</p>
